The Municipal Accountant consistently adopt the perpetual inventory method in the recording and accounting for all inventory items;

The Heads of concerned offices ensure that the RIS is prepared for each requisition of inventory or supply from stock; 

The Property Officer prepare the monthly SSMI to summarize the RIS issued during the period, and submit to the Municipal Accountant, including copies of the RIS, within five days after the end of the month for recording;

The Municipal Accountant prepare the journal entries to record the expenditures or the cost of various supplies and materials issued to end-users based on the respective SSMIs; 

The Local Chief Executive require the semestral physical count of the inventory of supplies and materials, the RPCI of which shall be submitted to the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively; and

The Property Officer and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the RPCI and their respective records, in case of discrepancies, and take up the necessary adjustments.

We reiterated our prior years’ recommendations that Management:

Stop the practice of giving different rates to JOs having the same position in the LGU in order not to create inequality in the work force of the LGU; and

Require the HRMO to adopt a schedule of standard rates for JOs per position that is based on qualification and the nature of work/assignment taking into consideration the prevailing minimum wage in the locality;

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to identify and establish the correct balance of the remaining Due to LGUs and Due to NGAs for each source agency and thereafter:   

Return to the concerned source agencies the unutilized balance of the fund transfer wherein the agreement requires the return thereof;

Revert to Government Equity the balances of fund transfers in the nature of financial assistance and subsidy wherein the agreement does not mention of the disposition of the unused balance and that future utilization thereof will be subject to the usual accounting, auditing and budgeting laws, rules and regulations; 

Retain special purpose funds; and  

Clean the books of accounts, particularly the accounts Due to LGUs and Due to NGAs, in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2016-005 in order to present fairly the Liability accounts in the financial statements.

We recommend that Management:

Make representations with the NHA and request for possible extension of payment or, if possible, condonation of the loan and delinquent interest;

Appropriate the necessary funds for the repayment of the NHA loan and the delinquent interest thereon to avoid further incurrence of unnecessary expenses like penalties or fines for non-payment of the said loan;

Exert extra effort to locate the supporting documents to determine the legitimacy and propriety of the claims under the PMF and revert to the Unappropriated Surplus of the General Fund the amount of ₱671,704.45, considering that it has been dormant for quite some time;

Conduct periodic review and monitoring of payable accounts so that these accounts will consist only of valid claims against the Municipality; and

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the Loans Payable-Domestic account as Current and Non-Current Liabilities for better presentation of liabilities of the LGU in the Statement of Financial Position as at the year-end/reporting date.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

Require all the above-mentioned seven (Item No. 1 to 7) payees who actually received the honoraria payments, to immediately refund the amount they received, to the Office of the Municipal Treasurer for want of valid and legal basis; 

