With the above-noted deficiencies, we recommendedand Management agreed to do the following courses of action:

5.) Prioritize the procurement of medicines and medical supplies considering that one of the important and primordial concern of the LGU is on basic health services, particularly those specific program funded from the national government and with specific time frame;

6.) Indicate carefully the specific formulation and packaging of medicines and drugs being requested in order for the supplier to bid accurately and eventually facilitate the delivery, inspection and acceptance;

7.) The Purchase Request  be  supported by specific certifications by the Budget Office for funding purposes pursuant to Section 360 of RA 7160, and be numbered right after it had been approved by the HOPE for proper control, hence, no need for the BAC to forward the same to the Budget Office ;

8.) The BAC see to it during the post-qualification process that the winning bidder is a duly authorized supplier or distributor by examining every Certificate of Product Registration (CPR) submitted vis-à-vis his or her Certificate of Distributorship;

9.) The Procuring Entity strictly observe legal timelines particularly in the approval of contracts and/or purchase orders;

10.)	The supporting documents for which originals cannot be submitted, such as LTOs and CPRs be properly authenticated by either BFAD or the BAC Secretariat based on the originals presented in order to ensure its regularity and validity; and

11.)The Management designate a permanent employee who has adequate knowledge and training in the inspection of medicines and drugs, since the conduct of inspection is not only limited to quantity, but most especially to quality of medicines and compliance of BFAD rules, in order to ensure that the medicines and drugs being procured and dispensed by the RHU is safe, efficacious and of good quality and most especially affordable to both the government and the ordinary citizen of the community.

We recommended and Management agreed that the following courses of action be undertaken:

12.) Require the Municipal Agriculture Officer being the Focal Person to conduct a thorough review of the MOA and see to it that every provision thereon is properly observed during the project implementation;

13.) Require the recipients Farmers’ Association to be accredited by the LGU being the implementing agency. Require also the recipients to submit their profile, certificate of registration and list of officers and members for attachment to the MOA and Project Proposal;

14.) 	Come up with a written policy to be adopted by the recipient farmers’ association regarding the use, maintenance as well as fees and rentals of the aforesaid farm implements together with the manner of accounting and design of the Reports they are going to submit to the LGU regarding their operations;

15.) 	Require the concerned farmers’ association to secure comprehensive insurance cover for the said properties in order to protect the interest of the government in case of loss and/or fortuitous events;

16.) 	Require the construction of a specific storage or shed to house and safeguard the Mechanical Rice Planter to protect it from burglars and/or natural elements;

17.) 	The LGU should look into the manner of acquisition or use by which the lot/site where the MPDP and FBD were constructed in order to comply with the MOA and ensure that no problem relative to ownership and use will arise in the future and during the effectivity of the agreements;

18.) 	For similar future procurement and in case of mixed procurement, it is the responsibility of the Procuring Entity to be guided by parameters and conditions in the relevant provisions of RA 9184 and its RIRR on what should be considered as Goods or Infrastructure Projects procurement depending upon the primary purpose of the contract. The plans and drawings as well as specifications of the FBD should be adequately prepared to serve as guide to the contractor in the performance of their contract as well as on the part of management in the supervision and inspection of the finished project;

19.) 	Hasten the implementation of the remaining five palay shed which were not yet started;

20.) 	Ensure the speedy official turnover of the farm implements to the recipients farmers’ beneficiaries in order for them to timely benefit there from;

21.) 	Activate the Project Monitoring Committee (PMC) in the monitoring the implementation and evaluation of different programs and projects implemented by the Municipality; and

22.) 	Require the Focal Person/s of the LGU in-charge in the implementation of BUBs Programs/Projects to prepare and submit and or comply with all the contractual provisions, terminal reports and post-implementation obligations.

We recommended and Management agreed to direct:

43.) The Bids and Awards Committee (BAC), particularly the BAC Secretariat to document the transactions and/or events as it transpired during the different phases of the procurement process to support its validity and propriety; 

44)  The GSO or concerned Department or Officials to impose strictly the terms and conditions, particularly on the posting of performance bonds and delivery dates, in such a way that performance bond are posted upon award prior to the execution of the Contract/PO, and see to it that procured items are delivered on time, otherwise imposed liquidated damages for late deliveries; 

45.) The Municipal Accountant to strengthen the processing/pre-audit activities, as part of the Agency’s overall accounting and internal control system, to avoid control overrides, and ensure that transactions being processed, paid and recorded are duly approved and supported with complete documentation and/or technical requirements. The use of Checklist provided for under the Revised Documentary Requirements for Common Government Transactions prescribed under COA Circular No. 2012-001 and the Revised RIRR of RA 9184 may prove useful as guide in the processing of claims for payment; and 

46.)  The BAC, GSO and Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking supporting documents, data and/or information for our review, as listed in Annex C, otherwise the related transactions may be suspended or disallowed in audit.
